<p>
An (ordinary) torus is a <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Surface.h=
tml">surface</a> having <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Genus.html=
">genus</a> one, and therefore possessing a single "<a href=3D"https://math=
world.wolfram.com/Hole.html">hole</a>"
 (left figure). The single-holed "ring" torus is known in older literature
 as an "anchor ring." It can be constructed from a <a href=3D"https://mathw=
orld.wolfram.com/Rectangle.html">rectangle</a>
 by gluing both pairs of opposite edges together with no twists (right figu=
re; Gardner
 1971, pp.&nbsp;15-17; Gray 1997, pp.&nbsp;323-324). The usual torus embedd=
ed in three-dimensional
 space is shaped like a donut, but the concept of the torus is extremely us=
eful in
 higher dimensional space as well.
</p>
<p>
In general, tori can also have multiple holes, with the term <img src=3D"ht=
tps://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/Torus/Inline1.svg" class=3D"in=
lineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D=
"9" height=3D"21" alt=3D"n">-torus used for a torus with <img src=3D"https:=
//mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/Torus/Inline2.svg" class=3D"inline=
formula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"9" =
height=3D"21" alt=3D"n"> holes. The special case of a 2-torus is sometimes =
called the
 <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/DoubleTorus.html">double torus</a=
>, the 3-torus is called the <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Tripl=
eTorus.html">triple
 torus</a>, and the usual single-holed torus is then simple called "the"
 or "a" torus.
</p>
<p>
A second definition for the <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/image=
s/equations/Torus/Inline3.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:=
100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"9" height=3D"21" alt=3D"n">-toru=
s
 relates to dimensionality. In one dimension, a line bends into circle, giv=
ing the
 1-torus. In two dimensions, a rectangle wraps to a usual torus, also calle=
d the 2-torus.
 In three dimensions, the cube wraps to form a 3-manifold, or 3-torus. In e=
ach case,
 the <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/Torus/Inlin=
e4.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" bo=
rder=3D"0" width=3D"9" height=3D"21" alt=3D"n">-torus is an object that exi=
sts in dimension
 <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/Torus/Inline5.s=
vg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=
=3D"0" width=3D"37" height=3D"21" alt=3D"n+1">. One of the more common uses=
