</p>
<p>
A torus with a <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Hole.html">hole</a>=
 in <i>its surface</i> can be turned inside out to yield an identical torus=
. A torus can be knotted externally or internally,
 but not both. These two cases are <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com=
/AmbientIsotopy.html">ambient isotopies</a>,
 but not <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/RegularIsotopy.html">regu=
lar isotopies</a>. There are therefore
 three possible ways of embedding a torus with zero or one <a href=3D"https=
://mathworld.wolfram.com/Knot.html">knot</a>.
</p>
