<p>
An arbitrary point <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equatio=
ns/Torus/Inline112.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;ma=
x-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"12" height=3D"21" alt=3D"P">
 on a torus (not lying in the <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/ima=
ges/equations/Torus/Inline113.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-hei=
ght:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"22" height=3D"21" alt=3D"xy"=
>-plane)
 can have four <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Circle.html">circle=
s</a> drawn through it. The first circle
 is in the plane of the torus and the second is <a href=3D"https://mathworl=
d.wolfram.com/Perpendicular.html">perpendicular</a>
 to it. The third and fourth <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Circl=
e.html">circles</a> are called <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Vil=
larceauCircles.html">Villarceau
 circles</a> (Villarceau 1848, Schmidt 1950, Coxeter 1969, Melnick 1983).
</p>
